==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hasp
<hw>Hasp</hw> <pr>(h⟦adot⟧sp)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hasp</ets>, <ets>hesp</ets>, AS. <ets>h⟦ae⟧pse</ets>; akin to G.
<ets>haspe</ets>, <ets>h⟦aum⟧spe</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>haspe</ets>,
Icel. <ets>hespa</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A clasp, especially a metal strap permanently fast
at one end to a staple or pin, while the other passes over a staple, and
is fastened by a padlock or a pin; also, a metallic hook for fastening a
door.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A spindle to wind yarn, thread, or silk
on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An instrument for cutting the surface of grass land;
a scarifier.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hasp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hasp
<hw>Hasp</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hasped</conjf> <pr>(h⟦adot⟧spt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hasping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>h⟦ae⟧psian</ets>.]</ety> <def>To shut or fasten with a
hasp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hassle</ent>⟦br⟧
